Features of the mitral stenosis murmur

The classic mid-diastolic low-pitched rumbling murmur of mitral stenosis with pre-systolic accentuation is best audible at the apex, in the left lateral position with the bell of the stethoscope. Pre-systolic accentuation usually means the presence of atrial contraction and hence sinus rhythm, but it may persist in AF following short diastoles [6]. The duration of the murmur is directly proportional to the severity of mitral stenosis, but the intensity of the murmur is not. The murmur can be heard provided the atrioventricular gradient remains above 3 mmHg [3]. Because diastolic mean gradient is directly related to heart rate, the manoeuvres that increase heart rate can help to detect an otherwise faint murmur . Source

  • The first heart sound is loud. (as leaflets are kept apart by the blood pressure gradient).
  • Sound becomes softer when the valves are thickened.
  • S2 depends depends on the severity of pulmonary hypertension.
  • Splitting narrows as pulmonary pressures rise.
  • Opening snap: high pitched early diastolic due to sudden tensing of valve leaflets
  • Increasing stenosis -> opening snap becomes closer to S2.

In patients with mixed rheumatic mitral valve disease, careful auscultation may help to find the predominant lesion. A loud S1, a prominent OS with a short A2-OS interval and a short systolic murmur favour predominant MS, whereas an S3 and soft S1 favour predominant MR.

[!INFO] Summary: Measles

Mmnemonic: Incubation - 1 to two weeks (8 to 14 days) ; phase 1 - lasts 4 days (at most), phase 2 begins at 4 days.
Infective - 4 days before onset of rash.

  • Phase 1 : catarrhal phase : rhinorrhoea, cough, conjunctivitis, koplik's spots in the oral mucosa (lasts 2 - 4 days)
  • Phase 2: Eruptive / exanthematous stage : rash that spreads form the head outward. (fades away in the same order) (occurs 2 - 4 days after onset of fever)
  • infective 4 days before and 2 days after onset of rash.
  • Rash lasts about a
  • Incubation period 8-14 days.
  • Droplet spread; highly infective.
  • No foetal abnormalities.

Occipital lobe strokes

Features:

  1. Homonymous visual field defects
  2. Central visual field defect
  3. Cortical blindness
  4. Alexis without agraphia (i.e patient can't read but can write because language isn't affected.

CRP

  • CRP was the first ⭐Pattern recognition receptor (PRR) to be identified.
  • Has proinflammatory and anti-inflammatory properties. Anti > pro.
  • Roles: Identifies and binds to foreign molecules and damaged local cells. ⭐Activates the classical [[#Complement system|complement]] pathway AND binds Fc receptors to facillitate phagocytosis - opsonin
  • CRP can be normal in SLE due to the production of interferons which inhibit hepatic CRP production.

Alcoholic hepatitis

  • AST : ALT ratio > 2 (rarely seen in other hepatic diseases) (UpToDate)
  • However, AST and ALT are usually less than 300, almost never exceed 500;
  • Alcohol abuse is associated with macrocytosis (exact cause is unknown). MCV can even be used as a surrogate marker for degree of alcohol abuse. (Mnemonic: The bigger your cells -> the more you've been drinking)

[!INFO] Mnemonic: S for "senter" of the acinus
The central acinal cells are rich in AST
Both AST and ALT enzymes require pyridoxal-5’-phosphate (vitamin B6) to function properly. Its absence in nutritionally-deficient heavy-drinkers has a much larger effect on the production of ALT than that of AST, causing the AST:ALT ratio to rise. A normal AST:ALT ratio should be <1.
⭐

  • Rh incompatibility causes severe disease because anti Rh antibodies are IgG antibodies which cross freely.

Intrahepatic Cholestasis of pregnancy

  • ALP and Gamma GT rise more than AST and ALT.
  • Presents with pruritus and jaundice in the Third trimester.
  • Treated with ursodeoxycholic acid.
  • Contrast with [[Hypertension in pregnancy#Acute fatty liver of pregnancy]], where patients have ALT / AST rise greater than ALP / Gamma GT and they are unwell, with neutrophilia.
